 division of labour, the (in)compatibility of women’s domestic and professional lives and the status and true value of women’s work that shaped eighteenth-century culture as surely as they shape our own.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aEnglish fictionxHistory and criticismx18th century. 0aEnglish fictionxHistory and criticismx19th century. 0aEnglish fictionxWomen authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aEnglish fictiony18th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aEnglish fictiony19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aLabor in literature. 0aWomen in literature. 0aWomenxEmploymentxHistoryx18th centuryxGreat Britain. 0aWomenxEmploymentxHistoryx19th centuryxGreat BritainxGreat Britain. 0aWomenxEmploymentzGreat BritainxHistoryy18th century. 0aWomenxEmploymentzGreat BritainxHistoryy19th century. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Women Authors.2bisacsh  aCharlotte Smith.  aLiterary Fund.  aMary Wollstonecraft.  aSarah Scott.  adivision of labour.  afemale-authored fiction.  agender.  awomen authors.  awomen's work.  awriting.1 aBatchelor, Jennie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagez978311128363040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978184779267940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781847792679423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781847792679/original  a978-3-11-128363-0  Manchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagec1986d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles